<span class="displaytext"><i>unveils new tv ad touting (candidate last)'s universal health care plan</i> <p>des moines, ia - the presidential campaign of senator (candidate full) today announced he will host a "senior town hall meeting" - bringing together senior citizens and high schools seniors -- in ames tomorrow. at the meeting, (candidate last) will answer questions and participate in a conversation about his vision for uniting americans, young and old, behind the effort to change washington. </p><p>"americans of all ages, from high school seniors to senior citizens, are tired of being divided by washington politicians looking to score political points," (candidate last) said. "we're building a grassroots movement of generations of americans who are ready to challenge the divisive, special interest-driven system in washington and unite the country around our shared values." </p><p>(candidate last)'s campaign will also begin airing a new 30-second television ad in iowa on friday in which (candidate last) highlights his commitment to changing the system in washington and reforming our nation's health care system. the ad, titled "mother", opens with (candidate last) talking directly to the camera about how his mother was burdened by a failing health care system as she battled cancer during the last few months of her life. to view the ad: <a href="http://my.(candidate full).com/page/content/mother">click here</a>. </p><p>"for twenty years washington's talked about health care reform and reformed nothing," (candidate last) says in the ad. "i've got a plan to cut costs and cover everyone. but unless we stop the bickering and the lobbyists, we'll be in the same place 20 years from now." </p><p>on friday, the quad city times will publish an op-ed from senator (candidate last) in which he writes about his commitment to strengthening social security and firmly opposing any effort to privatize social security.</p></span>



